<div id="review_3701654519" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3701654519" />
    <a title="Benjamin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/103284091-benjamin"><img alt="Benjamin" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3701654519?book_show_action=true">Dec 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Benjamin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Benjamin" href="/user/show/103284091-benjamin">Benjamin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/103284091-benjamin?shelf=gay-2000-2019">gay-2000-2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3701654519" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13966829116242358660">I am inclined to avoid novels about gay men written by women, with a few notable exceptions (Mary Renault, Marion Zimmer Bradley for example), they just fail to hit the mark. That so many (probably straight) female writers try to hide behind ambiguous names, (you know the sort: A. B. Cee, X. Y. Zed) suggests to me that they know this too. They just cannot avoid feminising their men.<br/><br/>This might not matter if it were not for the repercussions. Any search for decent gay literature is swamped with th</span>
  <span id="freeText13966829116242358660" style="display:none">I am inclined to avoid novels about gay men written by women, with a few notable exceptions (Mary Renault, Marion Zimmer Bradley for example), they just fail to hit the mark. That so many (probably straight) female writers try to hide behind ambiguous names, (you know the sort: A. B. Cee, X. Y. Zed) suggests to me that they know this too. They just cannot avoid feminising their men.<br /><br />This might not matter if it were not for the repercussions. Any search for decent gay literature is swamped with these female authors, not helped by the enthusiasm of their predominantly female readers who cause it to be promoted to the top spots in lists.<br /><br />The Boy Who Saw In Colours falls into this category, the two boys, Josef and Von, just don't behave like real boys once their friendship develops, especially as I imagine boys in their situation. <br /><br />More distracting than that however are two more serious failings. The writer no doubt knows what she is trying to convey, but some passages are simply misleading or confusing, they're sometimes hard to follow, including some dialogues, who's speaking and to whom? We are supposed to believe that this is the 1930s/1940s, yet that illusion is destroyed but their ready acceptance and use of the word gay. We're led to believe that these boys don't even know the derogatory meaning of the word faggot (or whatever German equivalent the author has in mind). Yet they freely banter with gay, a term for homosexual that while in usage since the C19th, was hardly known until the 1960s even in English-speaking countries; I was there, I remember. Once it started to occur in this novel, it destroyed the remainder of the book for me, pushing it to a contemporary setting. Would it not have been better to use a period appropriate German language word, or even the English word queer, (According to Wiktionary schwül is the German equivalent of gay, but I do not know if that was in common use during the period setting of this novel. Like gay, schwül has been in use since the mid to late C19th, but its common usage, again like gay, may have been more recent. But all that is research that is the author's responsibility, I should not have to be questioning it.) <br /><br />I started out rating this as a four to five-star book, but while writing this review I feel it must be less, I'd better stop here, or I might downgrade it further, a shame because it is potentially good.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="13966829116242358660" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


